# Perf and Type Hygiene Policy

## Scope and Change Hygiene
- Keep each commit and PR single-purpose: `perf`, `bugfix`, `type-stabilization`, or `refactor` only.
- Do not mix broad UI rewrites with performance or type cleanup.
- Stage only files relevant to the active scope.

## Performance Rules
- Prefer server-first data loading for critical routes and first paint.
- Avoid duplicate client fetches when initial data is already provided.
- Separate above-the-fold and below-the-fold loading when possible.
- In aggregators, fetch only data required by enabled sections/features.

## Type Safety Rules
- Do not silence errors with broad `any`/`unknown` casts.
- Use narrow interfaces, discriminated unions, and explicit type guards.
- For `catch (err: unknown)`, always normalize with `instanceof Error`.
- Type dynamic icons/components correctly (`LucideIcon` or `ComponentType`).

## API and Middleware Rules
- Use runtime-safe narrowing for external data and settings values.
- Keep fallback behavior explicit and non-breaking.
- Preserve existing runtime behavior while improving type safety.

## Hydration Safety Rules (SSR ↔ CSR parity)
- The first client render MUST produce HTML identical to the SSR output.
  Defer any browser-only or non-deterministic value to a post-mount `useEffect`.
- Never read `window`, `document`, `navigator`, `localStorage`, `sessionStorage`,
  `window.matchMedia`, `Date.now()`, or `Math.random()` inside a `useState`
  initializer or in the render body of a Client Component used during SSR.
  Initialize state to a deterministic default, then sync inside `useEffect`.
- Do NOT import `useReducedMotion` directly from `framer-motion`. Use
  `@/lib/useSafeReducedMotion` instead. The raw hook reads
  `prefers-reduced-motion` synchronously on the client and returns a value
  that differs from SSR (`null`), which causes hydration mismatches when used
  to branch on `motion.*` `initial`/`animate`/`transition` props or styles.
- For `next-themes`, gate any theme-dependent rendering (icons, classNames,
  conditional content driven by `resolvedTheme`) behind a `mounted` flag set
  in `useEffect`. Prefer Tailwind's `dark:` variant for theme-dependent
  styling so CSS — not React state — handles the difference.
- When a small, unavoidable attribute mismatch is acceptable on a single
  element (e.g. a known third-party-injected attribute), use
  `suppressHydrationWarning` narrowly on that element only — never to mask a
  real mismatch in a subtree.

## Animation Rules (framer-motion)
- Reach for `useSafeReducedMotion` (not the raw framer-motion hook) whenever
  motion preferences influence rendered output.
- Keep `motion.*` `initial` props deterministic across SSR/CSR. If the value
  must depend on a runtime preference, it must come from a hydration-safe
  source (see above) so the first paint matches SSR.
- Prefer `MotionConfig` at the layout level for app-wide motion defaults
  rather than ad-hoc per-component branching.

## Definition of Done (must pass before handoff)
- `npm run build` passes fully.
- Smoke-check core routes and critical APIs after substantial changes.
- No newly introduced lint/type errors in touched files.
- Include a short impact summary: what changed, why, risk, and verification steps.
